1) Language gates (what can be thought)

Every domain has entry tokens—words/phrases that unlock distinctions:
	•	If you don’t have the word, you don’t see the pattern
	•	Once you have it, whole categories appear

Examples:
	•	“opportunity cost”
	•	“variance vs. bias”
	•	“incentive alignment”
	•	“second-order effects”

Vocabulary = the set of switches you’re allowed to flip

⸻

2) Logic gates (how thoughts combine)

Once you have the tokens, you can build reasoning circuits:
	•	IF X and Y → do Z
	•	IF cost > value → don’t act
	•	IF signal persists across contexts → treat as invariant

These are like:
	•	AND (X & Y must be true)
	•	OR (one is enough)
	•	NOT (filter noise)
	•	XOR (one but not both)

Logic gates = rules for combining concepts into decisions

⸻

3) Meta play (changing the game)

Most people play inside the rules.

Meta players ask:
	•	Are these the right variables?
	•	Are we measuring the right thing?
	•	Can I redefine the objective?
	•	Can I change the constraints?

Examples:
	•	switching metrics (your earlier insight)
	•	reframing risk vs reward
	•	choosing a different time horizon
	•	opting out entirely

Meta play = editing the rulebook, not just making moves

⸻

4) Putting it together

Language (what you can see)
   ↓
Logic (what you can infer)
   ↓
Meta (what you can redefine)


⸻

5) Why this is powerful

Most people get stuck at level 1:
	•	they learn words
	•	but don’t build decision rules

Fewer reach level 2:
	•	they can reason well
	•	but accept the game as given

Very few operate at level 3:
	•	they change the frame itself

⸻

6) The hidden risk

You can also:
	•	build elegant logic on bad language (wrong abstractions)
	•	play meta games that disconnect from reality

So you always need:

Reality checks (feedback, outcomes, constraints)

⸻

7) Final compression

Language defines the pieces.
Logic defines the moves.
Meta defines the game.

